t Engineer Regiment. By 2003 the squadron was re-designated as '''1 Field Squadron'''. The squadron then deployed with 21 Engineer Regiment on [[Operation Telic]] two times; [[Operation Telic V]] (November 2004\u2014April 2005) and [[Operation Telic XI]] (December 2006\u2014June 2008). By 2008 following the Delivering Security in Changing World reforms of 2003, the 21st Engineer Regiment moved to [[Ripon Lines]] in [[Catterick Garrison|Catterick]] in 2008 along with the brigade they were supporting, the 4th Mechanised Brigade.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>Watson and Rinaldi, Corps of Royal Engineers ''Page 267''</ref><ref>Watson and Rinaldi, Corps of Royal Engineers ''Page 268''</ref><ref name=\":11\">Watson and Rinaldi, Corps of Royal Engineers ''Page 277''</ref> Just before move as a result of the Army 2020 reforms, the squadron had the following structure;<ref>Watson and Rinaldi, Corps of Royal Engineers ''Page 326''</ref>\n* Squadron Headquarters (2 FV436, 2 FV432, 3 Spartans, 1 FV432 Ambulance)\n** Administrative Echelon (No armoured vehicles assigned)\n** Fitters Section (1 FV434, 1 FV432, 1 Samson)\n* 1 Field Troop (42 Personnel) [1 Spartan and 5 FV432]\n* 2 Field Troop (Same as 1st) [Same as 1st]\n* 3 Field Troop (Same as 1st) [Same as 1st]\n* Support Troop (1 FV432, 1 Spartan, 4 CET)\n\nIn 2010 the initial Army 2020 reforms were announced, and the 21st Engineer Regiment was moved under control of the [[12 (Force Support) Engineer Group|12th Force Support Engineer Group]] [Being name to Force Support from Air Support in 2014], itself under the [[8th Engineer Brigade (United Kingdom)|8th Engineer Brigade]]. This group was initially assigned to support the army through engineering support and providing engineering to the Adaptable Force ([[1st (United Kingdom) Division]]).<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>Watson and Rinaldi, Corps of Royal Engineers ''Page 336''</ref> The regiment saw two more deployments in Afghanistan; [[Operation Herrick XII]] (April\u2014October 2010) and [[Operation Herrick XVII]] (October 2012\u2014April 2013).<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> Following the Army 2020 refines, the squadron is still part of 21 Engineer Regiment, now supporting the [[1st Strike Brigade]]. The squadron and regiment are currently based at [[Claro Barracks]].<ref>\u201c21 Engineer Regiment - British Army Website.\u201d ''The British Army'', [http://www.army.mod.uk/royalengineers/units/824.aspx http://www.army.mod.uk/royalengineers/units/824.aspx.]</ref><ref>\u201c21 Engineer Regiment.\u201d ''The British Army'', <nowiki>https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/corps-regiments-and-units/corps-of-royal-engineers/21-engineer-regiment/</nowiki>.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* The Monthly Army List, July 1914. (1914). [ebook] London, County of London, England: The War Office. Available at: <nowiki>https://deriv.nls.uk/dcn23/1032/4427/103244277.23.pdf</nowiki> [Accessed 13 Sep. 2019].\n* Watson Graham E and Rinaldi Richard A. The Corps of Royal Engineers: Organisation and Units 1889\u20132018. Tiger Lilly Books ISBN 9781717901804\n* \u201cBritish Army Units from 1945 On.\u201d ''British Army Units from 1945 on - 1 Squadron'', <nowiki>http://british-army-units1945on.co.uk/royal-engineers/squadrons/1-squadron.html</nowiki>.\n* Watson, Graham E. and Rinaldi, Richard A. The British Army in Germany (BAOR and After): An Organisational History 1947-2004 Tiger Lilly Publiscations LLC 2005. ISBN 0-9720296-9-9\n\n{{uncategorised|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "LucasA04", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1_Field_Engineer_Squadron"}
{"title_page": "Eric Anderson (teacher)", "text_new": "{{short description|British educator}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix = Sir\n| name = Eric Anderson\n| honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KT|FRSE}}\n| image = \n| birth_name = William Eric Kinloch Anderson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1936|5|27}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|04|22|1936|5|27}}\n| spouse = Poppy Mason\n| children = 2\n| education = [[George Watson's College]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of St Andrews]] (MA)<br/>[[Balliol College, Oxford]] (MLitt)\n| occupation = Academic\n}}\n\n'''Sir William Eric Kinloch Anderson''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=|KT|FRSE}} (27 May 1936 \u2013 22 April 2020) was a British teacher and educator, who was the [[Provost of Eton|provost]] of [[Eton College]] from September 2000 to January 2009.\n\n==Life and career==\n\nAnderson was born on 27 May 1936<ref name=Birth>{{cite news|title=Birthday's today |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/archive/2013-5-27.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |accessdate=24 May 2014 |date=27 May 2013 |quote=Sir Eric Anderson, Provost of Eton College, 2000\u201309, 77 years old}}</ref> and schooled at [[George Watson's College]], [[Edinburgh]]. He graduated from the [[University of St Andrews]] with [[First class honours degree#First-class honours|first-class honours]] in English language and literature and then a [[Master of Letters]] (MLitt) degree from [[Balliol College]], [[University of Oxford]].\n\nDuring his early career, Anderson taught at [[Fettes College]] in [[Edinburgh]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fettes.com/news-events/default-news-page/~board/fettes-college/post/sir-eric-anderson-former-staff-1959-1970|title=Sir Eric Anderson|website=Fettes College}}</ref> and at [[Gordonstoun]] where he taught [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]]. He moved to be headmaster at [[Abingdon School]] (1970\u201375) <ref name=AS>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/sir-eric-anderson/|title=Sir Eric Anderson|website=Abingdon School}}</ref>, [[Shrewsbury School]] (1975\u201380) and [[Eton College]] (1980\u201394) and he was rector of [[Lincoln College, Oxford]] (1994\u20132000). He was chairman of the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|Heritage Lottery Fund]] (1998\u20132001) and provost of [[Eton College]] (2000\u20132009).\n\nAt Fettes, he was [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]]'s housemaster. Blair subsequently named Anderson in a 1997 advertising campaign run by the [[Teacher Training Agency]], entitled \"No one forgets a good teacher\". Because Anderson was head master of Eton while [[David Cameron]] and [[Boris Johnson]] were there <ref name=AS/>, he was involved in the education of the heir to the British throne and three British prime ministers, as well as [[Justin Welby]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]. He was a supporter of the [[Direct grant grammar school|Direct Grant system]].<ref name=AS/>\n\nThe Clarendon Press published Anderson's edition of ''[[The Journal of Sir Walter Scott]]'' in 1972 and he became a trustee of Scott's [[Abbotsford House|Abbotsford]] during its refurbishment. He was elected a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] in 1985 and, in 2002, he was appointed a Knight of the [[Order of the Thistle]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=56780 |date=12 December 2002 |pages=15113\u201315114 }}</ref> \n\nHe retired as Provost of Eton on 30 January 2009,<ref>[http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/a/15159/(William)%20Eric%20Kinloch+ANDERSON.aspx Profile: Sir Eric Anderson, KT, FRSE], [[Debrett's]]</ref> and was succeeded by [[William Waldegrave, Baron Waldegrave of North Hill|William Waldegrave]].\n\nHis other positions included [[visitor]] at [[Harris Manchester College, Oxford]]; member of the visiting committee of Harvard University Memorial Church; [[trustee]] of the [[Royal Collection Trust]]; and chairman of [[Cumberland Lodge]]. He received honorary degrees from the [[University of St Andrews]], Hull, Siena, Birmingham, the [[University of Aberdeen]] and Buckingham.<ref>{{cite web|title=HRH The Duchess of Rothesay joins University 'family'|url=http://www.abdn.ac.uk/news/details-13923.php|publisher=University of Aberdeen}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAnderson was the son of William James Kinloch Anderson and Margaret Gouinlock Harper. He was married to Elizabeth (\"Poppy\") Anderson, daughter of William and Mary Mason of Skipton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fieldtree.blogspot.com/2012/12/sir-william-eric-kinloch-anderson.html|title=Sir William Eric Kinloch Anderson|last=Field|first=Ron|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> Their son is [[David Anderson (barrister)|David Anderson QC]] (Lord Anderson of Ipswich) and their daughter Kate is married to [[Will Gompertz]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/will-gompertz-we-are-all-artists-we-just-have-to-believe-it-that-s-what-artists-do-10389894.html|title=Will Gompertz: 'We are all artists. We just have to believe it. That's what artists do'|newspaper=The Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nHe was an Honorary [[List of Old Abingdonians|Old Abingdonian]] and in 2018 accompanied Poppy, Kate and Will Gompertz, to open Beech Court at Abingdon School.<ref name=AS/> \nAnderson died on 22 April 2020 at the age of 83.<ref>{{cite tweet |first=David |last=Anderson |author-link=David Anderson, Baron Anderson of Ipswich |user=bricksilk |number=1253244809931894786 |date=23 April 2020 |title=My father, a fine teacher, died yesterday... }}</ref><ref name=AS/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Old Abingdonians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Michael William McCrum]]\n| title=[[List of head masters of Eton College|Head Master of Eton College]]\n| years=1980\u20131994\n| after=[[John Lewis (headmaster)|John Lewis]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Maurice Shock]]\n| title=[[Rector (college)|Rector]] of [[Lincoln College, Oxford]]\n| years=1994\u20132000 \n| after=[[Paul Langford]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Provost of Eton]]\n| before=[[Antony Acland|Sir Antony Acland]]\n| after= [[William Waldegrave, Baron Waldegrave of North Hill|William Waldegrave]]\n| years=2000\u20132009\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Eton Head Masters}}\n{{Provosts of Eton College}}\n{{Rectors of Lincoln College, Oxford}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Eric}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at George Watson's College]]\n[[Category:Scottish schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Lincoln College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Thistle]]\n[[Category:Headmasters of Shrewsbury School]]\n[[Category:Rectors of Lincoln College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Head Masters of Eton College]]\n[[Category:Heads of Abingdon School]]\n[[Category:Staff of Abingdon School]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British educator}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix = Sir\n| name = Eric Anderson\n| honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KT|FRSE}}\n| image = \n| birth_name = William Eric Kinloch Anderson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1936|5|27}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|04|22|1936|5|27}}\n| spouse = Poppy Mason\n| children = 2\n| education = [[George Watson's College]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of St Andrews]] (MA)<br/>[[Balliol College, Oxford]] (MLitt)\n| occupation = Academic\n}}\n\n'''Sir William Eric Kinloch Anderson''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=|KT|FRSE}} (27 May 1936 \u2013 22 April 2020) was a British teacher and educator, who was the [[Provost of Eton|provost]] of [[Eton College]] from September 2000 to January 2009.\n\n==Life and career==\n\nAnderson was born on 27 May 1936<ref name=Birth>{{cite news|title=Birthday's today |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/archive/2013-5-27.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |accessdate=24 May 2014 |date=27 May 2013 |quote=Sir Eric Anderson, Provost of Eton College, 2000\u201309, 77 years old}}</ref> and schooled at [[George Watson's College]], [[Edinburgh]]. He graduated from the [[University of St Andrews]] with [[First class honours degree#First-class honours|first-class honours]] in English language and literature and then a [[Master of Letters]] (MLitt) degree from [[Balliol College]], [[University of Oxford]].\n\nDuring his early career, Anderson taught at [[Fettes College]] in [[Edinburgh]] and at [[Gordonstoun]] where he taught [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]]. He moved to be headmaster at [[Abingdon School]] (1970\u201375) <ref name=AS>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/sir-eric-anderson/|title=Sir Eric Anderson|website=Abingdon School}}</ref>, [[Shrewsbury School]] (1975\u201380) and [[Eton College]] (1980\u201394) and he was rector of [[Lincoln College, Oxford]] (1994\u20132000). He was chairman of the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|Heritage Lottery Fund]] (1998\u20132001) and provost of [[Eton College]] (2000\u20132009).\n\nAt Fettes, he was [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]]'s housemaster. Blair subsequently named Anderson in a 1997 advertising campaign run by the [[Teacher Training Agency]], entitled \"No one forgets a good teacher\". Because Anderson was head master of Eton while [[David Cameron]] and [[Boris Johnson]] were there <ref name=AS/>, he was involved in the education of the heir to the British throne and three British prime ministers, as well as [[Justin Welby]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]. He was a supporter of the [[Direct grant grammar school|Direct Grant system]].<ref name=AS/>\n\nThe Clarendon Press published Anderson's edition of ''[[The Journal of Sir Walter Scott]]'' in 1972 and he became a trustee of Scott's [[Abbotsford House|Abbotsford]] during its refurbishment. He was elected a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] in 1985 and, in 2002, he was appointed a Knight of the [[Order of the Thistle]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=56780 |date=12 December 2002 |pages=15113\u201315114 }}</ref> \n\nHe retired as Provost of Eton on 30 January 2009,<ref>[http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/a/15159/(William)%20Eric%20Kinloch+ANDERSON.aspx Profile: Sir Eric Anderson, KT, FRSE], [[Debrett's]]</ref> and was succeeded by [[William Waldegrave, Baron Waldegrave of North Hill|William Waldegrave]].\n\nHis other positions included [[visitor]] at [[Harris Manchester College, Oxford]]; member of the visiting committee of Harvard University Memorial Church; [[trustee]] of the [[Royal Collection Trust]]; and chairman of [[Cumberland Lodge]]. He received honorary degrees from the [[University of St Andrews]], Hull, Siena, Birmingham, the [[University of Aberdeen]] and Buckingham.<ref>{{cite web|title=HRH The Duchess of Rothesay joins University 'family'|url=http://www.abdn.ac.uk/news/details-13923.php|publisher=University of Aberdeen}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAnderson was the son of William James Kinloch Anderson and Margaret Gouinlock Harper. He was married to Elizabeth (\"Poppy\") Anderson, daughter of William and Mary Mason of Skipton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fieldtree.blogspot.com/2012/12/sir-william-eric-kinloch-anderson.html|title=Sir William Eric Kinloch Anderson|last=Field|first=Ron|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> Their son is [[David Anderson (barrister)|David Anderson QC]] (Lord Anderson of Ipswich) and their daughter Kate is married to [[Will Gompertz]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/will-gompertz-we-are-all-artists-we-just-have-to-believe-it-that-s-what-artists-do-10389894.html|title=Will Gompertz: 'We are all artists. We just have to believe it. That's what artists do'|newspaper=The Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nHe was an Honorary [[List of Old Abingdonians|Old Abingdonian]] and in 2018 accompanied Poppy, Kate and Will Gompertz, to open Beech Court at Abingdon School.<ref name=AS/> \nAnderson died on 22 April 2020 at the age of 83.<ref>{{cite tweet |first=David |last=Anderson |author-link=David Anderson, Baron Anderson of Ipswich |user=bricksilk |number=1253244809931894786 |date=23 April 2020 |title=My father, a fine teacher, died yesterday... }}</ref><ref name=AS/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Old Abingdonians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Michael William McCrum]]\n| title=[[List of head masters of Eton College|Head Master of Eton College]]\n| years=1980\u20131994\n| after=[[John Lewis (headmaster)|John Lewis]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Maurice Shock]]\n| title=[[Rector (college)|Rector]] of [[Lincoln College, Oxford]]\n| years=1994\u20132000 \n| after=[[Paul Langford]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Provost of Eton]]\n| before=[[Antony Acland|Sir Antony Acland]]\n| after= [[William Waldegrave, Baron Waldegrave of North Hill|William Waldegrave]]\n| years=2000\u20132009\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Eton Head Masters}}\n{{Provosts of Eton College}}\n{{Rectors of Lincoln College, Oxford}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Eric}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at George Watson's College]]\n[[Category:Scottish schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Lincoln College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Thistle]]\n[[Category:Headmasters of Shrewsbury School]]\n[[Category:Rectors of Lincoln College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Head Masters of Eton College]]\n[[Category:Heads of Abingdon School]]\n[[Category:Staff of Abingdon School]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "